20. What is the difference between CHAR and VARCHAR?
Use CHAR for fixed-length data and VARCHAR for variable-length data. CHAR wastes space but is slightly faster; VARCHAR saves space but is flexible.
CHAR(n)
Fixed-length data type
Always uses n bytes, regardless of actual string length
Pads unused space with spaces
Example:
CHAR(10) storing "Hi" → uses 10 characters ("Hi ")

VARCHAR(n)
Variable-length data type
Uses only the necessary space + 1 or 2 bytes for length tracking
No padding

Example:
VARCHAR(10) storing "Hi" → uses 2 bytes only
 


