45. A service keeps crashing. How do you check recent logs?
Most modern Linux distros use journalctl to manage logs in a centralized binary format. 
Recent logs for a specific service: Use journalctl -u <service-name>. Add -e to jump straight to the end of the logs.
Logs from the current boot: Use journalctl -b to ignore entries from before the most recent restart.
Time-filtered logs: Narrow down your search using journalctl --since "1 hour ago" or specific dates like journalctl --since "2024-02-05 12:00:00".
Error priority only: Run journalctl -p err -u <service-name> to hide informational messages and focus only on failures. 

