1. What is continuous testing
Continuous testing is the automated,, step-by-step process of evaluating software quality at every stage of the development lifecycle (SDLC). By integrating automated tests into the CI/CD pipeline, it provides immediate feedback on code changes, allowing developers to identify and fix defects early, which reduces risks, improves quality, and accelerates release cycles. 
Key Aspects of Continuous Testing
Automated Testing: It relies on automated scripts (unit, API, UI, performance, security) rather than manual testing to ensure rapid execution.
Early & Frequent Testing: Tests are executed immediately whenever code is changed, preventing bugs from accumulating.
Immediate Feedback: Developers receive instant, actionable feedback to fix errors immediately, promoting a "shift-left" approach (testing earlier in development).
DevOps & Agile Integration: It is a foundational component of DevOps and Agile, ensuring that development, testing, and operations work together.
Risk Mitigation: By testing throughout the process, organizations can prevent, rather than just detect, critical issues before they reach production. 
Continuous Testing vs. Traditional Testing
Traditional: Performed at specific intervals, typically at the end of development (e.g., in a "QA phase"), causing bottlenecks.
Continuous: Integrated directly into the CI/CD pipeline, running continuously through the "infinite loop" of software development. 
Benefits
Faster Delivery: Speeds up the software development life cycle (SDLC).
Higher Quality: Reduces risk of bugs and improves user experience.
Cost Efficiency: Catches issues earlier, which is cheaper than fixing them post-release. 

2.  What is SAST, DAST, and IAST ?
SAST, DAST, and IAST are essential, complementary application security testing methodologies. SAST (Static) analyzes source code for vulnerabilities early in development (white-box). DAST (Dynamic) tests running applications externally, mimicking hacker attacks (black-box). IAST (Interactive) combines both, using agents inside the application to monitor code execution during runtime. 
1. SAST (Static Application Security Testing) 
Approach: "White-box" testing; analyzes code, bytecode, or binaries without running the application.
When: Early in the development lifecycle (coding phase, CI/CD pipelines).
Pros: Identifies specific lines of code causing vulnerabilities, low cost to fix.
Cons: Higher false-positive rates; cannot detect runtime environment issues. 
2. DAST (Dynamic Application Security Testing)
Approach: "Black-box" testing; scans running applications by simulating attacks on inputs, endpoints, and APIs.
When: Later, during testing or staging phases.
Pros: Identifies runtime issues, configuration flaws, and authentication problems with low false positives.
Cons: Does not pinpoint the specific line of code; runs later in development. 
3. IAST (Interactive Application Security Testing) 
Approach: Hybrid "gray-box" testing; uses agents or instrumentation inside the application server to monitor behavior while the application runs (e.g., during functional testing).
When: During QA/testing phase.
Pros: Combines code-level visibility (SAST) with runtime context (DAST), provides real-time results with high accuracy.
Cons: Requires language-specific agents and setup within the application runtime. 
Comparison Summary
Feature 	SAST				DAST			IAST
Testing Type	White-box (Static)		Black-box (Dynamic)	Gray-box (Hybrid)
State		Non-running code		Running application	Running application
When to Use	Development (IDE/CI)		Testing/Staging		QA/Testing/CI
Fix Timing	Early (Cheap)			Late (Expensive)	During Testing
Accuracy	Lower (False Positives)		High			High (Low False Positives)
Identifies	Coding flaws, insecure libs	Server/Config flaws	Both (Code & Runtime)
Using a combination of these methods is best practice to maximize coverage across the entire software development lifecycle (SDLC). 
