3.What is the role of props.conf and transforms.conf during indexing?
In Splunk, props.conf and transforms.conf work together during the parsing phase of indexing to structure, enrich, and route data before it is written to disk. props.conf defines what rules to apply (e.g., source type, timestamps, breaking events), while transforms.conf provides the specific regex-based actions for data transformation, masking, or routing. 
Role of props.conf (The Directive)
Data Parsing: Defines how to break incoming data into individual events (LINE_BREAKER, SHOULD_LINEMERGE).
Timestamping: Configures how Splunk extracts and parses timestamps (TIME_PREFIX, TIME_FORMAT).
Source Type Identification: Assigns or updates source types (KV_MODE, REPORT).
Routing Reference: Directs data to transforms.conf for advanced manipulation using TRANSFORMS-<class>Splunk
Role of transforms.conf (The Executor)
Field Extraction: Uses regular expressions to extract fields at index-time, which is faster than search-time for large datasets.
Data Masking/Redaction: Masks sensitive information (e.g., SSN, credit card numbers) before indexing.
Routing/Filtering: Sends data to specific indexes or drops unnecessary data (nullQueue) based on regex matches.

4.What is index-time vs search-time field extraction? Give examples of each.
Index-time field extraction occurs when Splunk parses data during ingestion, saving fields to disk, which increases index size but speeds up searches. Search-time extraction occurs when running a search, using more CPU dynamically, offering better flexibility and performance for large datasets
Index-Time Field Extraction
When: Data is ingested (written to disk).
Pros: Fast search performance.
Cons: Higher storage cost, slows down indexing, rigid (hard to change).
Examples:
Default Metadata: host, source, sourcetype, and timestamp.
Configured Extraction: Using transforms.conf and props.conf (via TRANSFORMS-) to force specific fields to be indexed, such as extracting a transaction_id at ingestion.
Structured Data: Automatically parsing JSON or CSV fields when INDEXED_EXTRACTIONS is used. 
Search-Time Field Extraction
When: The user runs a search.
Pros: Flexible (easy to change), no extra storage cost.
Cons: Can be slower on huge datasets, uses more CPU at search time.

5.What are the default Splunk buckets (hot, warm, cold, frozen)? What triggers a bucket roll?
Splunk buckets manage data retention by moving data through stages—Hot, Warm, Cold, and Frozen—based on age and size constraints. Hot buckets are active for writing, then roll to Warm (searchable, old data), Cold (slower storage), and finally Frozen (archived or deleted). A bucket rolls (Hot$\rightarrow$Warm) when it hits maxDataSize or maxHotSpanSecs, while Warm/Cold rolls are triggered by capacity (maxWarmDBCount) or retention policies. 
Default Splunk Bucket Stages
Hot: Currently active buckets where new data is written. Fully searchable.
Warm: Data that is no longer being actively written to, but still frequently searched. Rolled from Hot.
Cold: Older data moved from Warm to cheaper, slower storage, still searchable.
Frozen: Data that has exceeded retention policies. It is either deleted or archived.
Thawed: Data that has been restored from a Frozen state for searching

6.Where do you configure line breaking and timestamp extraction for new data?
Line breaking and timestamp extraction for new data in Splunk are configured in the props.conf file, typically located on indexers or heavy forwarders in $SPLUNK_HOME/etc/system/local/ or within a custom app directory. Key settings include LINE_BREAKER for splitting events and TIME_FORMAT for timestamp recognition.
Key Configuration Areas:
props.conf (Indexer/Heavy Forwarder): This is the primary location for parsing configurations.
Line Breaking: Use LINE_BREAKER = <regular_expression> (often with SHOULD_LINEMERGE = false) to define event boundaries.
Timestamps: Use TIME_FORMAT = <strptime_format>, TIME_PREFIX = <regex>, and MAX_TIMESTAMP_LOOKAHEAD to define how to identify and parse the time.
Data Input Stage (Settings > Data Inputs): When ingesting new data, you can configure these settings in the GUI, which writes to props.conf.
Universal Forwarders: While parsing usually happens at the indexer, you can enable event breaking at the source using props.conf on a Universal Forwarder if necessary. 

7.What is indexer acknowledgment and why does it matter for reliability?
 Indexer acknowledgment is an optional, advanced configuration in Splunk forwarders that ensures data is not lost during transmission to an indexer. It acts as a confirmation mechanism, where the forwarder keeps a copy of the data in memory until the indexer confirms that it has received, processed, and successfully written the data to its file system. If no acknowledgment is received, the forwarder automatically resends the data.
Prevents Data Loss: It guards against loss of in-flight data. Without it, a forwarder considers data "sent" as soon as it leaves its network socket, regardless of whether the indexer crashed or failed to write it.
Handles Node Failures: In clustered environments, if an indexer goes down or is unable to process data, the forwarder will not receive an acknowledgment and will instead try to resend the data to another healthy node.
Ensures Successful Indexing: It confirms that the data was not only received but also actually indexed.
Ensures Data Replication: In a clustered environment (e.g., Replication Factor 3), the acknowledgment is sent back only after the source indexer has written the data to its disk and replicated it to its target peers. 
Key Considerations and Trade-offs
Performance Impact: Enabling this feature introduces latency because the forwarder must wait for acknowledgments. It is generally not recommended for scenarios where performance is more critical than 100% data guarantee.
Potential for Duplicates: If a network issue prevents the acknowledgment from returning to the forwarder, even if the indexer successfully wrote the data, the forwarder may resend the data, resulting in duplicates.
Memory Usage: It significantly increases the memory usage of the forwarder (by default, expanding the wait queue from 500KB to 28MB). 
How it Works
Send: The forwarder sends data in blocks (approx. 64kB).
Hold: The forwarder keeps a copy of the block in its "wait queue" in memory.
Acknowledge: The indexer receives the data, parses it, writes it to disk, and then sends an acknowledgment back.
Release/Retry: Upon receiving the acknowledgment, the forwarder removes the data from memory. If it does not receive one, it resends the data (usually to a different node if load-balancing is configured)

