Splunk Architecture (Non-Negotiable)
You should clearly understand:
Deployment Types
Standalone -  self contained server
Distributed - enables horizontal scaling by separating the search head (user interface/query management) from multiple indexers (data storage/searching).
Search Head Cluster (SHC) - a group of two or more search heads that share configurations, search jobs, and knowledge objects, ensuring high availability and consistent search results

Indexer Cluster - a high-availability architecture where a group of indexers (peer nodes) replicate data, ensuring multiple copies exist for data retention, fault tolerance, and search capability

Deployment Server
Deployment Server is a centralized management component. It distributes configurations, apps, and content updates to forwarders, indexers, and search heads. it manages group of clients.
Centralized Configuration: Enables administrators to manage and update configurations remotely, reducing manual effort. 

Heavy Forwarder
instance used to collect, parse, mask, and route data before sending it to indexers. 
It processes data, reducing load on indexers. HFs are ideal for complex routing, filtering sensitive data, or using modular inputs. 


Components
Forwarders, Indexers, and Search Heads

Universal Forwarder
The Splunk Universal Forwarder (UF) is a lightweight, dedicated version of Splunk Enterprise used to collect, tag, and securely stream data (logs, configurations, metrics) from remote servers to a central Splunk indexer. It has a low resource footprint, supports multiple platforms, and is designed to handle high-volume data forwarding without parsing it locally. 
Lightweight Agent:
Secure Data Transfer
Efficient Data Collection
Scalable:
Universal Forwarders (UF) are lightweight agents designed for high-performance data collection and forwarding without parsing. Heavy Forwarders (HF) are full Splunk Enterprise instances that parse, filter, and mask data locally before forwarding. Use UFs for standard data ingestion and HFs for advanced data manipulation or pre-parsing.

Indexer
Indexer is a core component of processing data.
Receives raw data and transforms it into searchable events, including metadata extraction (time, host, source, sourcetype)
Stores data in "buckets" on disk, which are highly optimized for fast search performance

Search Head
It manages search requests, directing queries to indexers and merging results for users. It provides the graphical interface (UI) for searching, reporting, and dashboarding, acting as the primary interaction point for analysts.

Cluster Master
Manages the overall health and configuration of the indexer cluster.
It controls data replication, bucket management, and configuration bundles, ensuring high availability and data searchability.

License Master
Data Flow
Source → Forwarder → Parsing → Indexing → Search
