67. What is the difference between declarative and scripted pipelines in Jenkins?
Declarative pipelines provide a more structured and simpler syntax, offering a predefined way of defining stages, steps, and post-build actions. It is more suited for users who want to quickly define a pipeline with less complexity.
Scripted pipelines offer more flexibility and control, allowing users to write pipeline logic in Groovy. It's better for complex use cases where custom behaviors and fine-grained control are needed.
68. What is the difference between a Jenkins master and a Jenkins agent?
The Jenkins master is the central server that manages Jenkins' web interface, job scheduling, and orchestration. It is responsible for managing the configuration, jobs, and reporting.
Jenkins agents (or slaves) are remote machines that execute the build jobs assigned by the Jenkins master. They help offload the job execution and allow Jenkins to scale by distributing workload across multiple machines.
69. What are the differences between Jenkins and AWS CodePipeline?
Jenkins is a highly customizable open-source CI/CD server that can run on any infrastructure (on-premises or cloud). It has a vast plugin ecosystem and supports integration with multiple tools and services.
AWS CodePipeline is a fully managed CI/CD service from Amazon that is specifically built to work with AWS services. It is simpler to set up for AWS-based workflows but offers fewer customization options compared to Jenkins.
70. What is the difference between using the "stash" and "unstash" steps in Jenkins pipelines versus using workspace persistency?
The "stash" step temporarily stores files in the pipeline's workspace, allowing them to be accessed in other pipeline stages or jobs. "Unstash" retrieves these files.
Workspace persistency keeps files in the workspace throughout the execution of a job. Stashing is particularly useful when you need to transfer files between different stages or jobs, whereas workspace persistency is for keeping files available throughout the entire job lifecycle.
71. What is the difference between Jenkins’ built-in build tools and using custom build tools in your pipeline?
Built-in build tools like Maven, Gradle, or JDK are preconfigured within Jenkins and can be used directly without needing special setup in your pipeline.
Custom build tools refer to tools that you define or install for your project needs. For example, you may need a specific version of a tool not available in Jenkins' default tool configuration. You specify these tools in your pipeline using the tool block.
72. What is the difference between Jenkins polling of SCM and triggering builds with a webhook from GitHub?
SCM polling makes Jenkins periodically check the source code repository for changes and triggers builds when a change is detected.
Webhooks push updates from GitHub to Jenkins whenever a commit occurs, triggering builds instantly. Webhooks are more efficient since they don't require periodic checking.
